# Cursor Rules – Complete Reference Guide

This document summarizes all four rule types in Cursor and provides editable templates.

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# 1. ALWAYS RULES

## Definition

Always rules are automatically included in every AI prompt. They act as global constraints.

## When to Use

* Enforcing architecture (e.g., MVVM)
* Coding standards
* Non-negotiable constraints

## Example Template

```md
---
type: always
---

- Use MVVM architecture
- Use Kotlin for Android development
- Follow clean architecture principles
```

---------------------------------------------------------------

# 2. AUTO ATTACHED RULES

## Definition

These rules are automatically applied when specific files (via glob patterns) are used.

## When to Use

* File-specific logic
* Module-based rules
* Platform-specific behavior

## Example Template

```md
---
type: auto-attached
globs: *.kt
---

- Use Kotlin best practices
- Avoid null pointer exceptions
- Prefer coroutines over callbacks
```

## Example (Android TV)

```md
---
type: auto-attached
globs: tv/**
---

- Ensure proper D-pad navigation
- Handle focus states explicitly
- Use focusable modifiers
```

---------------------------------------------------------------


# 3. AGENT REQUESTED RULES

## Definition

These rules are optionally used by the AI when relevant. The AI decides based on the description.

## Key Requirement

A strong, clear description is mandatory.

## When to Use

* Reusable logic
* Optional workflows
* Domain-specific guidance

## Example Template

```md
---
type: agent-requested
description: Use when creating API services in Android using Retrofit and Coroutines.
---

- Use Retrofit interfaces
- Use suspend functions
- Handle errors properly
- Return Result or Response
```

## Example (ViewModel)

```md
---
type: agent-requested
description: Use when creating or modifying ViewModel in Android using MVVM and StateFlow.
---

- Use StateFlow for UI state
- Expose immutable state
- Use viewModelScope for coroutines
- Avoid holding context
```

---------------------------------------------------------------

# 4. MANUAL RULES

## Definition

These rules are applied only when explicitly referenced using @ruleName.

## When to Use

* One-time workflows
* Special templates
* Debugging or migrations

## Example Template

```md
---
type: manual
name: generate-compose-ui
---

- Create reusable composables
- Follow Material design
- Keep UI stateless where possible
```

## Usage Example

```
@generate-compose-ui
```

---

# COMPARISON SUMMARY

| Rule Type       | Trigger              | Control | Predictability |
| --------------- | -------------------- | ------- | -------------- |
| Always          | Always active        | High    | Very High      |
| Auto Attached   | File pattern match   | Medium  | High           |
| Agent Requested | AI decides           | Low     | Medium         |
| Manual          | Explicit (@ruleName) | Full    | Very High      |

---

# BEST PRACTICES

* Use Always for strict rules
* Use Auto Attached for file-based behavior
* Use Agent Requested for reusable intelligence
* Use Manual for explicit workflows

